mod_proxy_msrpc - Change Log
============================

2026-04-19  Arno van der Veen <arno@itssecured.nl>

    FIX: RDG_IN_DATA / RDG_OUT_DATA not registered (Defect present since UTM 9.1, May 2013)

    Defect:
        The module registered only RPC_IN_DATA and RPC_OUT_DATA via ap_method_register().
        The RDG_IN_DATA and RDG_OUT_DATA HTTP method verbs used by Microsoft RDS Gateway
        (MS-TSGU protocol specification, Windows Server 2012+) were never registered.
        As a result, Apache declined all RDS Gateway tunnel requests with the log message:
            [proxy_msrpc:debug] mod_proxy_msrpc.c(604):
            declining due to bad method: RDG_OUT_DATA

    Impact:
        RDS Gateway sessions published through an Apache-based WAF/reverse proxy
        (including Sophos UTM and SFOS Web Application Firewall) failed unconditionally.
        All affected deployments from UTM 9.1 (May 2013) to SFOS v22.0.0 GA-Build411
        (April 2026) were unable to proxy RDS Gateway connections.

    Fix:
        - Added MSRPC_M_RDG_IN and MSRPC_M_RDG_OUT to the method enum in mod_proxy_msrpc.c
        - Registered RDG_IN_DATA and RDG_OUT_DATA via ap_method_register() in the init hook
        - Extended all handler conditionals (method check, PDU parsing, PDU length
          validation, session state, tunnel sync) to cover both RDG verb pairs alongside
          the existing RPC verb pairs

    Evidence:
        Live debug log from SFOS v22.0.0 GA-Build411 (17 April 2026):
            [proxy_msrpc:debug] mod_proxy_msrpc.c(604):
            declining due to bad method: RDG_OUT_DATA

    Reported by:    Arno van der Veen / itssecured.nl
    Sophos case:    03152113
    Bugcrowd:       9bb5f540-c573-4a24-8476-1c10a89b51a0
    References:     MS-TSGU specification (ms-tsgu), MS-RPCH specification (ms-rpch)

    Follow-up (same date):
        Extended the default User-Agent check to accept MS-RDGateway/1.0 without
        requiring explicit OutlookAnywhereUserAgents configuration. Acceptance is
        gated on the request method already being MSRPC_M_RDG_IN or MSRPC_M_RDG_OUT,
        so the existing MSRPC/RPC-over-HTTP path is not affected in any way.

    Known related issue (not in this module):
        The nDPI library contains an off-by-one error in its RPC_OUT_DATA detection:
        strncmp is called with length 11 instead of the correct 12, causing a partial
        match against the 11-character string "RPC_OUT_DAT". This is a separate defect
        in nDPI and does not affect mod_proxy_msrpc.
